<td><table width="100%" border="0" cellspacing="5" cellpadding="5" align="CENTER">
<tr>
<td valign="MIDDLE"><font face="Verdana" size="2" color="000000">My 2 coppers....<p>

Earth pets - good for soloing.  If you are in a group with someone who can snare (or snare and fear), bonds of force, or any spells that slow the mob down then kill your earth pet and use a different one such as air or water (fire would be useless unless it is being hit).  When a mob is rooted, they can attack.  When they are snared and running away from you or below 25% hit points left, then they will not attack you.<p>

Water pets are resistant to poison.  This makes them valuable if you are fighting poison based mobs such as Crag Spiders, Heart Spiders, Black Widows, etc.  <p>

Air pets do cast stun which will interrupt casters. This is important early on and to some extent as you travel in higher level dungeons (in full groups).  <p>

However, their invisibility is only effective up to a certain point.  Many dungeons are filled with casters and most casters see through invis.  By the time you visit Sol Dungeon you will find that EVERYTHING in that dungeon sees through invis so the benefit of any "surprise" doesn't exist.  <p>

Also as you rise in levels you will find that where you may have been able to summon a yellow or possibly even a red pet at level 8, you will be hard pressed to summon a pet 5 or more levels below you at mid to higher levels.  Since you will be going into these dungeons at these levels, you will find that your pet will agro mobs that you wouldn't if you were travelling without the pet.  Now some dungeons the mobs agro on everything anyway, so it may be a moot point, but one to consider.</font></td></tr></table></td></tr><tr bgcolor="DDDDDD">
<td><table width="100%" border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" align="CENTER">
