<td valign="MIDDLE"><font face="Verdana" size="2" color="000000">Well this was good advice for me, I'll be sure to try kiting it once I have Jboots, or if I happen to group with someone that can SOW.  I've never asked for a SOW, and have only had it cast on me when I was travelling with a druid.<p>

My comment about tanking myself was completely based on my own experience, and wasn't meant to say it would work for every level.  It does help though if you're worried about your pet dying, I know we can't take a whole lot of damage.<p>

I'm still sticking with my strategy of healing the fire pet, while using him as the main tank when soloing or in a small group.  A druid friend of mine also level 13 fought the peg-leg camp in BB.  There were 3 blue bandits, 1 green, and peg-leg who was white to us.  I had my fire pet go after peg leg, and used the first half of my mana bar to heal him.  That fire shield works excellent...by the time peg leg fell and I switched my targeting, I saw the other 4 bandits were all almost dead just from trying to hit my pet!  I used the rest of my mana to burn the other mobs down.  So my point here is just that (in my experience) a fire pet works great when you have a multitude of weaker mobs attacking him.  All you have to do is keep him alive and that fire shield will really make a big difference.  This strategy has also worked very well against death beetles in unrest.  Not bad experience for me (they're still blue to me, hehe), and with my fire pet we can take 2 or 3 at a time solo.<p>

