<tr>
<td><a href="UltraBoard.cgi?Action=ShowProfile&ID=vitaminlsd&Board=magician&Idle=30&Sort=0&Order=Descend&Page=0&Session=" target="Profile" OnMouseOver="window.status='View Meddle (vitaminlsd) Profile.';return true;" OnMouseOut="window.status=''"><font face="Verdana" size="1" color="000000 ">Profile</font></a></td><td align="RIGHT"></td></tr></table></td></tr><tr bgcolor="EEEEEE">
<td><table width="100%" border="0" cellspacing="5" cellpadding="5" align="CENTER">
<tr>
<td valign="MIDDLE"><font face="Verdana" size="2" color="000000">A lot of you have valid points, good opinions, and others I disagree with.  Rather than argue, I will simply post my feelings on the subject of pets.<p>

I am a 31st level magician.  Here is the lowdown on pets, as I have observed, at higher levels (24+)<p>

Earth - at my level, I rarely use earth anymore.  The only time I use earth is when dueling, to keep my opponent away from me while I blast.  Earth pet is great don't get me wrong, but I will tell you why I prefer other ones.  It has the highest strength, but the lowest agi and dex.  This means when it hits, it will hit hard, but due to low dex it will not hit as often as a fire, water, or air pet.  Since the agi is so low, it tanks poorly even though it has the highest hitpoints.  It gets hit hard over and over and I have had many earth pets run out of HPS on me in the thick of battle.<p>

Water - I also do not use water unless fighting a poisonous opponent.  Someone stated before that water and fire pets nuke does the same damage, this is not true.  Water pet's WaterElementalAttack spell damage is calculated with this formula: (lvl*2).  For instance, a pet that is level 24 (cons 24, not lvl 24 spell) would do 48 damage per cast.  Water is helpful in some situations, when at a fast spawn or fighting poisonous creatures.  It does have the best regen of all the pets, and well rounded stats.  However I find that there is usually another pet better suited to what I am trying to accomplish.<p>

Fire - The best group pet, assuming you have good tanks.  Reasons why:  First of all, you can keep your pet from taking too much damage by using /pet no taunt.  This will keep it from taunting the mob, therefore causing less damage to itself and having the tanks of the group take the main damage.  Secondly, the fire pet does the most damage, period.  It has the highest agi and dex, and its strength is second to only the earth pet.  Since the earth pet has low dex, it doesn't connect nearly as much so the fire pet does more melee damage.  The high agi means it can evade the most hits, and given sword of runes (which procs 40 damage) will do even more damage (thanks to it's high dex).  Then you add its damage shield, which is figured with this formula: (lvl/2)  For instance, a level 27 fire pet (cons 27, from a lvl 29 spell) will have a damage shield of approximately 13 dmg.  Fire does have the least hps, so it is not well suited for soloing.  However they are outstanding in groups and the mobs fall quickly.<p>

Air - My favorite pet at my level for soloing.  This is why: first of all, it has high agi and dex.  Give it sword of runes, and it will proc for 40dd, and evade lots of hits.  It also attacks the fastest of all pets, having about a 15% faster delay than the rest.  It ALSO has a stun spell, which generally lasts about 3-5 seconds.  This is how I solo with air pet.  I buff pet, giving him burnout II and med up until full again, then I cast inferno shield (13 pt DS) on him.  Next I malise the mob, lowering all his resists and making him much less likely to resist my pets stun.  At this point the mob is running towards me.  I back up and once the mob is good and close I send pet on him.  (This strategy requires jboots or sow btw)  I have pet taunt turned off, so mob will come after me.  I nuke mob, mob chases me while pet is at his heels whacking away and procing like mad.  Every time my pet uses stun spell on the mob, I stop running and nuke it.  I keep running in a circle as my pet follows the mob around beating it into submission.  The pet doesn't take much damage, and I don't take any.  I end up using about 50% of my mana, and this method has not failed for me yet.  Air pets are not great at low levels, but at about 24 and higher they start to come into their own.<p>

In closing, your mileage may vary.  Everyone's play style requires different tactics, and the way I learned to use pets effectively was with trial and error.  Overall have fun, and do what best suits you.  EQ is, after all, a game.  If ya don't have fun, what's the point!?<p>

Kjata Holythunder<br>
Magician of Tunare</font></td></tr></table></td></tr><tr bgcolor="DDDDDD">
