<td width="10"><img src="http://www.maximumeq.com/forum/Images/SmallNew.gif" border="0" alt="New Message"></td><td width="50%"><font face="Verdana" size="1" color="EEEEEE"><b>RE:PETS (modified 0 times)</b> </font></td><td width="50%" align="RIGHT"><font face="Verdana" size="1" color="EEEEEE"><b>Mikal</b></font></td></tr></table></td></tr><tr bgcolor="DDDDDD">
<td><table width="100%" border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" align="CENTER">
<tr>
<td><a href="UltraBoard.cgi?Action=ShowProfile&ID=mikal&Board=magician&Idle=30&Sort=0&Order=Descend&Page=0&Session=" target="Profile" OnMouseOver="window.status='View Mikal (mikal) Profile.';return true;" OnMouseOut="window.status=''"><font face="Verdana" size="1" color="000000 ">Profile</font></a></td><td align="RIGHT"></td></tr></table></td></tr><tr bgcolor="EEEEEE">
<td><table width="100%" border="0" cellspacing="5" cellpadding="5" align="CENTER">
<tr>
<td valign="MIDDLE"><font face="Verdana" size="2" color="000000">This thread is a few weeks old, but I thought I'd add my own thoughts on it.  Have a level 24 mage, but been playing since July '99 (so, yes, have had lots of other characters as well).  Since the thread started with an evaluation of pets, went into Kiting, and covered some other areas, I've strayed some in this message to cover all those areas.  Remeber, these are just My Own Humble Opinions.  You're milage may vary, simply due to the way you like to melee, cast, or evac.<p>

First, Pet Delay.  The delay of attack on all pets is the same now -- 30.  Has been for months.  Used to be different, and unfortunately there's lots of old info on the Internet.  But all hit the same now.  So, decide which to use by their unique capabilities, not because you think one is going to get an attack in quicker than another.<p>

Second, Pet Spells.  While they look cool, pet spells are actually bad for you.  People have asked in the past for a "no spellcast" option, like the "no taunt" option.  Were told by official Verant rep (Gordon Wrinn) that this would never happen, it would unbalance things.  Originally, pets didn't cast spells; they just meleed.  But other classes complained about pets being too strong, so the casting was added.  Testing shows pet spells pretty reliably at (level+1), not any (level*2) as some keep mentioning for the water pet.  Why this is bad:  take for example a pet you create post-lvl 29.  It's going to dual-wield, bash, I think kick and dual-hit as well.  Give it two of your summoned swords, and you get proc's as well.  Every round of combat your pet casts, it's going to do substanially less damage than if it had been allowed to fight instead.  <p>

Three, Experience.  Decide if you want to level quickly or safely.  The Difference?  The 50%+ experience penalty if the pet does more damage to the MOB than you do.  If you want to level, then expect to use up mana nuking down the MOB.  The pet is just a distraction, trying to keep the MOB from getting to you.  MOBs have short memories.  You can burn them down, doing more than 50% damage, without them aggroing onto you.  The key is to do smaller burns spread throughout the fight, rather than 2 or 3 massive burns right at the beginning.  That just gets their attention way too early.<p>

Four, Focus Items.  Focus items are said to work only at lvl 34 and above, but tests show this not to be true.  There's a pet stat enhancement effect which seems to work on *any* level pet summoning.  And there's a change to the pet visible model that makes the pet appear larger when summoned while holding a Focus Item.  It's this that doesn't show till level 34.  So, if you get a chance at the focus items, regardless of level, grab'em.<p>

Five, Melee.  Melee the MOBs some if you can, even if your pet is not in danger (in fact, better if they aren't in danger).  The reason?  What the ATK and AC values shown in the Persona page don't tell you is the big difference the unshown stats do:  offense, defense, and especially dodge.  These are listed in with the "skills" section, because they rise in level thru use, and cap at values dependent upon your level.  But these values are used in the computation of how much damage you take.  Have a high dodge value, for example, and when some MOB someday surprises you, you'll plain-and-simply get hit *less* than if your dodge value was low.  Same with defense, which mitigates the damage the hits do, and with offense when you try to fight back.  Now, these values are capped far lower than any melee players, and once you reach the max cap, there's no point to continue trying to improve them.  I'm not suggesting you pretend to be a Warrior.  But at least try to get these stats up to max.<p>

Six, Fireshields.  It's said that the Mage cast damage shields, when struck by a Mob, cause the damage done to be attributed to the damage shield itself, not the player wearing the shield.  It's like the damage shield is a player unto itself.  This seems to be due to some shortcuts Verant took in the programming of how shields work.  Why is this important?  Because when soloing, if your pet or yourself is meleeing and wearing a damageshield, it's that much damage that the Pet won't need to deal before the Mob is dead, and so the better the chance the Pet won't take 50% of the experience.  Because Verant has shown several areas where they've taken shortcuts like this, my own guess is that the Fire Pet fireshield works in exactly the same way as the player cast shields.  And because it does more damage than the Mage cast shield,  you get an even greater margin of safety.  This gives the Fire pet an added edge, I think.  Plus, the Fire pet's shield seems to last much longer than the Mage cast shields.  (Used to be mage fire shields cast on pets would last 10-15 minutes, even though it would only last a minute or so on players.  This was a bug fixed several months back, and now the mage cast shields fade as quickly off of pets as they do players.)<p>

Seven, Kiting.  Most of the posts here dealt with Kiting Mobs, and which pet would be best for this.  Here are my thoughts.  <p>

(1) How often are you soloing Mobs that you actually have SoW on?  Personally, very rarely.  Journeyman Boots are just not going to happen for me, because i don't belong to a guild and don't have the level or camping time to acquire them.  So, I need a Kiting stratagy that applies for a normal, non-speedy Mage.<p>

(2) Remember point 3 above.  You really don't want to be kiting if you're looking for experience.  Send in the pet, to get the Mob's attention, and then burn the best way you can till till the Mob's dead.  In these cases, I'd suggest using the Earth pet.  Attack with the earth pet till the Mob is rooted, pull the earth pet back, then nuke the Mob till it's done.  Send in the earth pet if the root breaks during the battle, or once you're satisfied you've done enough damage.  The pet acts as a shield, and you're basically using the Wizard stratagy of root-and-nuke.  Good if you have Clarity or Breeze cast on you (which happens to me about as often as SoW).  Also good if there isn't room to do much running around.<p>

(3) OK, you want to conserve mana.  You want to somehow burn up the major portion of the Mobs health, and have the rest taken care of by the Pet.  Realize that for kiting to work you have to: get the Mob's attention, have it chase you around while the pet is dealing damage to it, that at some point the Mob may  turn back and fight the pet, and that you then have to regain the Mob's interest and startup the chase.  My call there is to use the Fire pet.   Nuke the Mob heavy first, to get it chasing you.  Have the pet attack.  If the Mob stops to fight the pet, nuke it some more till it follows again, then keep running.  If you have a lead, most things in the non-Kunark lands won't catch up too quickly, giving the pet time to beat on it.  Why use a Fire pet? Well, while the Mob is chasing you, any one of the pets would do about as much damage with their melee attacks.  But the Air and Earth spell attacks don't do any damage; in fact they interfere with the point of kiting, which is to keep the Mob unsuccessfully chasing *you* while the pet deals damage from behind. Water and Fire, on the other hand, will be doing damage with spells, so the time they waste casting isn't nearly as useless (point 2 above).  When that Mob takes a moment to turn back and beat up on the pet again, the Fire pet has its (relatively) great Fireshield to add another source of damage.  I also think the Fire pet has better agility than the Water pet, so it won't get hit as often and will last longer.  My own feeling: since you're Kiting, your pet should never be in danger of running out of hitpoints.  Therefore, Earth or Water having more hitpoints than Fire doesn't really matter.  If you're counting on the hitpoints to save the pet, then the pet is getting hit way too often and, really by definition, you're not actually kiting.<p>

(4) If you have SoW on, or Journeyman boots, I'd still suggest using the Fire, or even Water, pet.  For the same reasons as given in the point above -- the more the Mob is hitting your pet instead of chasing you, the *less* you're actually kiting. And, most likely, the less the damage you've done to the Mob (so you're in danger of losing 50% of the experience as well).<p>

Eight, Pet Armor.  Pets can wear armor, and most people don't seem to realize this.  Work on your tailoring skill, and carry around tailoring patterns of the 3 or 4 highest AC items (tunic, pants, boots, sleeves is what i carry).  When you find a ruined pelt, or have one left over from that last annoying lion attack, make up patchwork armor to give your pet.  Give it a heatstone as well.  All totaled, you're going to give your pet a rise of 20 AC (that's from ACs of 6 + 4 + 4 + 3 + 3) -- how hard have you worked to get much smaller rises than that?  It appears to me to make a difference; try it for yourself and see.  Doesn't seem to matter whether the ruined pelts are wolf, cat, or bear; all seem to work.  I think NPCs are neutral on class and size restrictions, which is why you'll often see NPCs carrying non-class-allowed weapons other players have given them as jokes.  (Remember, the system treats Pets as NPCs, which is why they can go berserk, outlive their masters and go on killing sprees of player characters; and why the summoned sword proc works for them on everything, not just summoned Mobs.)<p>

<br>
Well, that's enough. Long-winded, but i hope it's all useful info.  See what you think, and I'll 'Cya on the Planes one day!<p>

Mikal<br>
Brell Serelis</font></td></tr></table></td></tr><tr bgcolor="DDDDDD">
